Exploring Ford GoBike Data 2019¶

by Tonima Ferdous¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Ford GoBike was a regional public bicycle sharing system in California's San Francisco Bay Area, operated by Ford Motor Company from 2017 to 2019 [1]. Ford GoBike System Data 2019 includes information about individual rides made in this bike sharing program in February 2019.

# extract days from the 'start_time' column to create a 'start_time_day' column
td_clean['start_time_day'] = pd.to_datetime(td_clean['start_time']).dt.strftime('%A')
# extract hours from the 'start_time' column to create a 'start_time_hour' column
td_clean['start_time_hour'] = pd.to_datetime(td_clean['start_time']).dt.hour
# extract hours from the 'end_time' column to create a 'end_time_hour' column
td_clean['end_time_hour'] = pd.to_datetime(td_clean['end_time']).dt.hour
In [22]:
# calculate age of the members from 'member_birth_year' column
td_clean['age'] = 2019 - td_clean['member_birth_year']

I first converted the null values in the 'age' column to 0. However, it created an issue later with the visualization and log-scale plotting. Therefore, it's better to keep them as they are.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset provides 183,412 entries of bike share statistics for various age group and customer base. The bike share schedule and pattern of the users are reflected in this data set. We have the following variables in the 17 columns.

duration_min: quantitative, continuous
start_time & end_time: quantitative, continuous
age: quantitative, discrete
ids: categorical, nominal
station names: categorical, nominal
user_type : categorical, nominal
member_gender: categorical, nominal
bike_share_for_all_trip: categorical, nominal

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I would like to examine the bikesharing pattern and schedule depending on various user types.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect age and gender of the members will play an important role determining the duration of rides. Also, timing of the trips and location would reveal some valuable information on their trip patterns.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will investigate distributions of individual variables. If any unusual points or outliers are noticed, it will be examined to clean things up.
I will start by looking at the user group—age, subscription policy, gender, and whether or not riders are enrolled in the bike share for all trip program.

There are 89.2% subscribed members and 10.8% causal customers.
74.6% male, 23.3% female, and 2.1% other gender type. It looks like some members did not disclose their gender while subscribing to this program. We'll investigae this further in the Bivariate Exploration section.
Bike share for all trip is a discounted program for the low-income community[3]. Looks like the program was not very popular among the San Franciso people. The plot shows that 90.5% bikers did not register for the bike share for all trip program; only a 9.5% did.

We'll now explore the age of the riders. From the descriptive statistics, the mean age of users is found 32 with a standard deviation of 12.

# countplot of start_time_day

sb.countplot(data = td_clean, x = 'start_time_day', color = default_color, order = start_time_day_order)
# get the current tick locations and labels
locs, labels = plt.xticks(rotation=90) 
# loop through each pair of locations and labels
for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):

    # get the text property for the label to get the correct count
    count = start_day_counts[label.get_text()]
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_td_clean)

    # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
    plt.text(loc, count+2, pct_string, ha = 'center', color = 'black');

GoBike trip frequency is highest on Thursdays, followed by Tuesdays and Wednesdays, respectively, in February 2019. Mondays have the fewest trips among the weekdays. Our interpretation is that Mondays are likely the day when people are least organized as they return after the weekend and might take more time biking to workplaces. People get progressively readier to use the service during the week. Friday is the day most people will take off from work if making a long weekend or are more likely to work from home—thus reducing the service demand. GoBike is less popular during weekends. The number of trips taken on Thursdays is about 55% higher than Sundays.

GoBike is popular among office commuters working with tech companies like Uber, Twitter located at Market Street, San Francisco [2]. Other popular riding stations are located near major public transport hubs i.e. Caltrain Train Station, San Francisco Ferry Building (Harry Bridges Plaza) and The Embarcadero at Sansome St. The bike share system is popular among those who commute from outside of the city for work. Those that live in the city are less likely than average to be car owners. This also applies to those commuting by public transport. Moreover, the young and environmentally concious workforce prefers to use bikes.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Among the variables of interests, there are member age and trip duration. Both of the columns contained some high-value points which produced long-tailed distributions. Therefore, members over 100 years and trip durations over 100 minutes were filtered out of the data. Also, a log-scale was applied to the histograms. As a result of this transformation, the age distribution now looks unimodal with the peak at 32 and the trip duration histogram also looks normal with with a peak near 9 minutes.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The quality and tidiness issues were cleaned in the preliminary data wrangling section. During the univariate explorating, outliers were observed in age (72 entries) and trip duration (909 entries). It was very difficult to examine each of the high-value outliers to find out the inconsistancies. Therefore, members over 100 years of age and trip durations over 100 minutes were filtered out of the data.

Bivariate Exploration¶

In this section, relationships between pairs of variables will be investigated.

In [44]:
# variables of interests 
numeric_vars = ['age', 'duration_min', 'start_time_hour', 'end_time_hour']
categoric_vars = ['user_type', 'member_gender', 'stat_time_day']

For numeric variables, it would be useful to create a correlation matrix as part of the bivariate exploration. The correlation matrices will be plotted as a heat map to make it easier to see the strength of the relationships. The center of this diverging color map is set to 0. The map uses hue to tell if a correlation is positive or negative, and determines its strength from the hue's intensity.

We'll also consider creating a plot matrix as a preliminary option to explore the relationship of our numeric variables. By default, PairGrid plots the same variables on the horizontal and vertical axes. On the diagonals, where the row and column variables match, a histogram is plotted. Off the diagonals, a scatterplot between the two variables is created.

In [47]:
# plot matrix: sample 500 trip data so that plots are clearer and
# they render faster
samples = np.random.choice(df1.shape[0], 500, replace = False)
trip_samp = df1.loc[samples,:]

g = sb.PairGrid(data = trip_samp, vars = numeric_vars)
g = g.map_diag(plt.hist, bins = 20)
g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter);

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

  • Duration and Age: We have noticed an inverse relationship between these two variables. Trip duration decreases in general as age increses, as expected.
  • Duration and User Type: Trips taken by the customers are usually longer compared to the subscribers.
  • Duration and Member Gender: Female riders took longer trips compared to the males. We'll examine this finding further in the next section.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

  • User Type and Member Gender: Higher percentage of males are subscribed members compared to the females. Only 1 in 8 female riders have bought the subscription. On the other hand, the subscriber to customer ratio is 6:1 in male members.
  • Age and Member Gender: Plots do not show any strong relationship. However, the other gender group has a small percentage of riders between 50 and 60 years, which is much higher compared to male and female riders.
  • User Type and Start Time: We found a similar distribution for subscribers and customers. The histograms are bimodal with spikes in 8 am and 5 pm. However, the count of trips are 25% higher at 5 pm compared to 8 am in customers. Looks like customers are more likely to rent a bike while returning from work and then leave the bike at some other time.

Multivariate Exploration¶

In this section of data analysis, I'll create plots of three or more variables to investigate the Ford GoBike data even further.
The main thing I want to explore in this part is how trip duration is influenced by user type, user gender, and age. Trip duration can be also influenced by days and hours of the week when the users starts a trip. To understand the duration pattern, location of the GoBike stations will also come into play.
We'll now use FacetGrid to create a multivariate plot with our primary features of interests—user, age, gender, and duration.

In [60]:
# FacetGrid scatterplot for user_type, age, gender, and duration_min
g = sb.FacetGrid(data = df1, col = 'member_gender', col_order = member_gender_order, row = 'user_type', row_order = user_type_order, height = 5, aspect = 1, 
                margin_titles = True)
g.map(plt.scatter, 'age', 'duration_min')

g.add_legend();

Subscription policy does not determine trip durations, but, age does. With age, duration becomes smaller. The plots does not even display any major difference in the trip durations for various genders (for subscribers and customers, both). We'll try another kind of plot to dig out if there is any interesting fact hidden.
Among the customers, over 70 years riders are less in numbers, irrespective of any gender. However, among the subscribers, the percentage of riders over 70 years are higher, even in females. There is a high rate of duration (about 60 mins) is observed in other gender at 68 years, which is very unusual and surprizing.

In [61]:

In [62]:
# user, member gender, and duration boxplot
# apply y-limit to avoid some outliers
plt.figure(figsize = [8,6])
ax = sb.boxplot(x= 'user_type', y= 'duration_min', hue = 'member_gender', data= df1,
                 order=['Subscriber', 'Customer'])
plt.ylim(0, 60)
plt.legend(loc = 6, bbox_to_anchor = (1.0, 0.5));# legend to right of figure

Although the quantity of subscribers is 87.8% larger than the customers, customers have a higher trip duration than subscribers in avarage. We assume that the subscribed riders follow a regular schedule for commuting to work or study. Therefore, their trip durations are more or less the same through out the month. On the other hand, riders who do not subscribed to the plan, are occasional users of GoBike. They do not need bikes everyday, and rent bikes for special schedules which are likely for long hours.
Interestingly, though the quantity of male riders is 68.7% higher than the females, we can see that female riders are taking longer trips compared to the males. One assumption is that, female bikers usually take a little longer to bike the same distance compared to the males. So, their trip duration goes up. Moreover, females might use bikes to trip more places than males, not only commute to work or school, but they might run errands in bike.

We'll now generate a plot with user, gender, duration, and start time. We'll use catplot() to combine a boxplot() and a FacetGrid. This allows grouping within additional categorical variables. Using catplot() is safer than using FacetGrid directly, as it ensures synchronization of variable order across facets.

Again, we observe that customers take longer trips than subscribers through out the week. We've already made an assumption to this in the user, gender, and duration exploration. Specially, on Saturdays and Sundays casual riders are found to bike longer than othe days of the week.
Interestingly, female users are found to take long rides compared to males. Particulary, on the weekends, females are observed biking for long hours.

With the casual customers, a surprising number of old-aged people are found to bike on Sundays, about 68 years, which is the maximum value in the distribution. May be they just loved taking a joy ride on Sundays. San Franciso weather is generally cool in February, which did not prevent that age group from biking.

A heatmap is generated to examine the mean duration for different days and hours. Instead of providing the original dataframe, we need to summarize the counts into a matrix that will then be plotted.

In [71]:
# data preparation
df_mean = pd.DataFrame(df1.groupby(['start_time_day', 'start_time_hour']).mean()['duration_min'])
df_mean = df_mean.reset_index()
# convert the 'start_time_day' column from a plain object type into an ordered categorical type
start_time_day_classes = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']
dayclasses = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=start_time_day_classes)
df_mean.start_time_day = df_mean.start_time_day.astype(dayclasses);
In [72]:
# use DataFrame.pivot() to rearrange the data, to have days of the week on rows
df_mean = df_mean.pivot_table(values = 'duration_min', index = 'start_time_day', columns = 'start_time_hour')
# plot heatmap
plt.figure(figsize = [14,8])
sb.heatmap(df_mean, annot = True, fmt = '.1f', cbar_kws = {'label':'mean trip duration'}, cmap = 'coolwarm')
plt.title('Mean Trip Duration for Days and Hours');

Higher trip durations are observed during the weekends. The mean duration is highest on Saturdays and Sundays between 4 am and 5 pm, about 16 to 12 minutes. It can be assumed that, during weekends, users bike to places other than their works and study, and spend more time on the road. Among the working days, Mondays and Thursdays have higher trip durations, about 10 to 14 minutes. Although Mondays have the lowest trips taken (14.6%) among the weekdays, frequencies of 12 minutes trips are much higher. Our interpretation is that Mondays are likely the day when people are least organized as they return after the weekend and might take more time biking to workplaces. People get progressively readier to use the service during the week.
